  "prompt": "What is a 3-regular planar graph?",
  "response": "A 3-regular planar graph is a graph with specific properties:\n\n1. **3-regular:** This means that every vertex in the graph has exactly three edges incident to it. In other words, each vertex has a degree of 3.\n   \n2. **Planar:** The graph can be drawn on a plane without any edges crossing each other. This property ensures that the graph can be represented in two dimensions without overlapping edges.\n\nA typical example of a 3-regular planar graph is the 3-polyhedron graphs, which include various forms of cubic graphs or graphs representing polyhedra like the cuboctahedron, tetrahedron, octahedron, and other such structures. The most famous 3-regular planar graph is the Petersen graph, although it is not itself planar but has a planar representation through graph embeddings.\n\nUnderstanding whether a 3-regular graph can be planar involves checking for properties such as the graph obeying Euler's formula (V - E + F = 2 for planar graphs with a connected structure, where V is the number of vertices, E is the number of edges, and F is the number of faces). Additionally, Kuratowski\u2019s theorem can be applied to see if subgraphs homeomorphic to K_{5} (complete graph on 5 vertices) or K_{3,3} (complete bipartite graph on 6 vertices) exist within the graph, which would imply non-planarity.\n\nFinding examples and constructing these graphs typically involves significant combinatorial and geometric considerations.",
